our current goal is about 9% protein content for the flour. we may adjust if needed, we'll see. 

    AI actually has these recommendations, which kind of are exactly that: 

        50% All-Purpose + 50% Pastry Flour: Brings the protein content down to ~9-10%, ideal for fluffy but not overly delicate pancakes.
        75% All-Purpose + 25% Cake Flour: Slightly softer pancakes, still with good structure.
        Add-ins: A tablespoon of cornstarch per cup of flour can also reduce toughness and improve tenderness.

        It claims you want the protein % down to like 8-10% 

another interesting option is to use spelt. it has 9-12% protein, and is often used interchangeably with all-purpose flour. 

=======================================================
MAKING THE BATTER 
=======================================================

1) fully whisk dry ingredients together

2) fully whisk wet ingredients separately (maybe wait until the end to whisk and add the egg)

3) combine wet & dry gently, just until no dry streaks remain 
    (it took ~27 stirs when I tried it)
    scrape around the bottom to get pockets of flour
    as soon as you stop seeing dry flour stop mixing 
    good to use a glass bowl so you can see the flour 
    
4) let rest for ~15-30min. lumps are okay - they'll hydrate and smooth out during resting

5) the pancakes are done when you see bubbles, they pop and the hole remains (it doesn't dissolve) 

6) make sure you add salted butter to the pancakes while they're warm

7) you can put finished pancakes in a low oven (150-200) while cooking the rest 

note: pastry flour tends to absorb a bit less liquid, so your batter might be thinner.
        if it looks too runny reduce buttermilk by 1–2 tablespoons or add 1–2 teaspoons extra flour.

