___________________________
My ideal derived recipe: 
1 cup flour (50/50 italian all-purpose and tip 00)
1.7 tbsp sugar
1.25 tbsp baking powder 
5/8 tsp salt 
1/2 tsp baking soda 

9/10ths cup buttermilk 
3 tbsp butter (melted, unsalted) 
1 large egg 
1.5-1.7 tsp vanilla extract (but I may lower this to 1 tsp next time)

AIs critiques: 
    Salt: 5/8 tsp is a little high for just 1 cup flour. Most recipes use ½ tsp per cup. 
        Yours is slightly above that, so pancakes may taste a bit salty.
    Baking Powder: 1.25 tbsp is on the upper end for 1 cup flour. 
        It should work, but if you notice a metallic or bitter aftertaste, reduce to 1 tbsp.
    Buttermilk: 0.9 cup is fine, but if batter feels too thick, you might need a splash more (up to 1 cup).
        (since I'm using tipo 00 the 0.9 actually makes sense / is consistent with AIs earlier recommendation)

My critiques after trying it: 
    Overall they were very good, but maybe we could improve a few things: 
    - We were at 1.5-1.7 tsp vanilla. I thought the pancakes may have had too much vanilla, 
        and I didn't put the entire amount in... I probably put 1.25 in. 
        Maybe try AIs recommendation of 1 tsp vanilla, or even less. 
        according to AI: 
            Most classic recipes use 1/2 to 1 tsp per cup of flour.
            1/2 tsp gives a subtle background note.
            1 tsp gives a clear vanilla flavor without overpowering.
            1.25 tsp is fine if you want a strong vanilla presence, but it’s edging toward dessert-like.
            If you want balanced flavor, go with 1 tsp.
            If you love vanilla-forward pancakes, keep 1.25 tsp.
            If you want the flour and buttermilk to shine more, drop to 1/2 tsp.
    - The batter felt almost too thick. However, that may have been why it rose so well. 
        I could try adding slightly more buttermilk next time... but I liked how the pancakes turned out. 
        They had incredible rise. So maybe I'll just cook them slower - our burners were on '4'. 
        I'll have to find out what temperature that is and adjust accordingly. Maybe try 3.5 next time. 
        I'd like to keep the batter ratio just due to the incredible amount of lift we got.
        If I am removing vanilla though I will need some more buttermilk... 
            maybe .95 cups makes sense. Although I don't think I got all 3 tbsp of butter in either.

