AIs "balanced" recommendation after looking at the other recipes:

1 & 1/4 cups flour (16g)                
1.5 - 2 tbsp sugar                      // for mild sweetness - not dessert-level
1 - 1.25 tbsp baking powder             // enough lift without bitterness. usually 1-1.25 per cup of flour 
1/2 - 5/8 tsp salt                      // flavor without overpowering - around 1/2 tsp per cup of flour
1/2 tsp baking soda                     // usually 1/2 tsp per cup of buttermilk

1 cup buttermilk 
2-3 tbsp butter (melted, unsalted)      // rich but not greasy
1 large egg 
1 tsp vanilla extract                   // pleasant aroma without dominating


=======================================================
RESTING THE BATTER 
=======================================================

Why let the batter rest if the baking powder is reacting once it gets wet? 
    because it'll react again when heat hits it, but letting the batter rest 
    allows the flour to fully absorb moisture and it allows the gluten strands to relax 
        letting the gluten strands relax is especially important if it was mixed too much. 
    also, small bubbles are still forming within the batter from the banking powder as it rests, they don't all dissipate, it's heavy batter. 
        but if you were to let the batter rest too long those bubbles would dissipate 

    ideal time to let the batter rest: ~15 min apparently. Babbish thinks 30 min... he's probably right. we'll go with 30 

=======================================================
AMOUNT OF STIRRING  
=======================================================

overmixing the battery actually creates 2 problems: 
    1) it overactivates gluten, causing a chewy pancake 
    2) it breaks up the bubbles released by the baking powder, reducing fluffiness
        thicker batters (like pancake batter) are more sensitive to bubble loss. 
        thinner batters (like crepes) can tolerate more mixing

Babbish says to stir or whisk lightly until you see no more dry ingredients 

=======================================================
PAN HEAT  
=======================================================

375F is the recommended heat according to AI, who cites America's test kitchen / Serious Eats 
    which matches medium-low to medium on most burners, apparently. 

    but this is above the smoke point of butter, which I find dubious 

    I saw one chef recommending NOT putting butter in the pan, but rather adding it afterwards... 

    another option is to use ghee 

whatever temperature we settle on will require an infrared thermometer, 
    or a griddle with a temperature setting

worth noting: 
    thicker batter may need a slightly lower heat to cook through fully 
    also, egg-rich or sugar-rich batters will burn easier, so use slightly lower heat 
    resting the batter also helps the pancake cook evenly 


